      "text": "When pressed, most smokers fall back on \"it's just a habit.\" But habits are easy to change when there's no drug underneath. You change small habits constantly. Drive on the other side of the road in a foreign country and you adapt within a day, with mild concentration and no anguish. If smoking were merely a habit, you'd have dropped it years ago — it's filthy, expensive, and you already want to be free of it.\n\nThe reason it resists is that it isn't a habit. It's an addiction wrapped in a belief. Calling it \"a habit\" is comforting because habits feel breakable and harmless. But naming it accurately — nicotine addiction maintained by an illusion of pleasure — is what actually sets you up to walk away."
